page_data: Dear Customer, Welcome to the TATA MOTORS family. We congratulate you on the purchase of your new vehicle and are privileged to have you as our valued customer. We urge you to read this Owner's Manual carefully and familiarize yourself with the equipment descriptions and operating instructions before driving. Always carry out prescribed service / maintenance work as well as any required repairs at an authorized TATA MOTORS Dealers or Authorized Service Centres (TASCs). Use only genuine parts for continued reliability, safety and performance of your vehicle. You are welcome to contact our dealer or Customer Assistance toll free no. (1800 209 8282) in case of any query or support required. We wish you a safe and pleasant driving experience.

page_data: IMPORTANT INFORMATION In this Owners Manual, you will find the text under the heading WARNING and NOTE which highlights important infor mation. Pay particular attention to these highlighted messages. Safety Tips Safe Driving Safety consciousness not only ensures your safety and the safety of other road users, but it also helps to reduce the wear and tear on your vehicle. Safe driving depends on: Always take into account the road con ditions, weather conditions, vehicle speed in order to prevent accidents. Turn ON the side indicators at least 30 meters before taking a turn or changing the lane. How quickly you make decisions to avoid an accident. Your ability to concentrate. Decelerate to a safe speed before tak ing turn. Do not apply brakes during cornering. How well you can see and judge ob jects. When overtaking other vehicles, watch out for the oncoming vehicle. How well familiar you are with your ve hicle controls and its capabilities. test Never drive under the influence of al cohol or drugs. If your vehicle is equipped with info tainment/navigation system, set and make changes to your travel route only when the vehicle is parked. Program radio presets with the vehicle parked, and use your programmed presets to make radio use quicker and simpler. NOTE Indicates additional information that will assist you in gaining the optimum ben efit and care for your vehicle. WARNING Indicates procedures or information that must be followed precisely in order to avoid the possibility of severe personal injury and serious damage to the vehi cle. NOTE Fatigue is a result of physical or mental exertion that impairs judgment. Driver fatigue may be due to inadequate sleep, extended work hours, strenuous work or non-work activities or combina tion of other factors. Take rest at regular intervals.

page_data: Driving on a Rainy Day Driving Through Water Do not drive through flooded areas. Judge the depth of water before driving through it. Otherwise, water may enter the vehicle interior or the engine compartment. If at all the situation demands that you have to drive through water then; Check wiper blades, lights and brakes for proper functioning and condition. Check the tyre treads depth, the con dition of the tread and tyre. Keep engine in higher RPM and crawl the vehicle in low gear. Avoid harsh braking and sharp turns. It may cause loss of control and lead to a skid. For slowing down, shift to lower gears and brake gently. Keep lights ON if visibility is poor. Driving on Wet Roads On wet road or during light showers, Aquaplaning can occur. Aquaplaning is the loss of direct contact between the road surface and the vehicles tires due to a water film forming between them. Steering or braking the vehicle can be very difficult, and loss of control can occur. There is no hard and fast rule about aquaplaning. The best advice is to slow down when the road is wet. Night Driving Flowing or rushing water creates strong forces. Driving through flowing water could cause the vehicle to about trying to drive through flowing water. Ensure that all lights are working and windshield, window glasses are clean. Drive more slowly at night than in the daytime, as the visual range is re stricted at night. Maintain a speed such that you can stop within illuminated distance of head lamps. Lightly apply the brake pedal to dry the liners until the brakes work normally once you are out of water. Do not use the high beam unless in evitable. It may dazzle the driver of the oncoming vehicle, thus causing an ac cident. Use head lamp main/dip beam to alert other road users on turns/ cross roads. Use side indicators for lane change or turning. NOTE If you have driven for a long time in heavy rain without braking, there may be a delayed reaction from the brakes when braking for the first time. You have to press the brake pedal more firmly. Maintain a greater distance from the ve hicle in front. WARNING Do not attempt to start the engine if ve hicle gets flooded due to water. Tow the vehicle to a safe place. Contact a near est TATA MOTORS Authorised Service Centre

page_data: Driving on Gradients When climbing gradient, the vehicle may begin to slow down and show a lack of power. If this happens, shift to a lower gear and apply power smoothly so that there is no loss of traction. When driving down a hill, the engine braking should be used by shifting into a lower gear. Do not drive in neutral gear or switch off the engine. Driving on Highway Stopping distance progressively, in creases with vehicle speed. Maintain a sufficient distance between your vehicle and the vehicle ahead. For long distance driving, perform safety checks before starting a trip and take rest at certain intervals to prevent fatigue. WARNING On long and steep gradients you must reduce the load on the brakes by shift ing early to a lower gear. This allows you to take advantage of the engine braking effect and helps avoid over heating of service brakes resulting in re duced braking efficiency.

page_data: SEAT BELTS This section of user manual describes your vehicles seat belt, airbag and Child restraints system. Please read and follow all these instructions carefully to minimise risk of severe injury or death. abdomen. To remove slack, pull up a bit on the shoulder seat belt. To loosen the lap portion seat belt if it is too tight, tilt the tongue and pull on the lap seat belt. A snug seat belt reduces the risk of sliding under the seat belt in a colli sion. Ensure that the seat belt running over the body (shoulder segment and lap segment) does not have any twist. Twisted seat belt may not offer effec tive protection when required. Releasing the Seat Belt To release the seat belt, push the red but ton on the lock buckle. The seat belt will automatically retract to its stowed position. If necessary, slide the tongue down the webbing to allow the seat belt to retract fully. Seat belts are the primary restraints system in the vehicle. All occupants, including the driver, should always wear their seat belts to minimize the risk of injury. Sit back and adjust the front seat. Make sure that your seat is adjusted to a good driving position and the back of the seat is upright. Buckling the Shoulder Seat Belt Grasp the tongue then slowly pull out the seat belt over the shoulder and across the chest. When the seat belt is long enough to fit, insert the tongue into the lock buckle until you hear a CLICK which indicates that the seat belt is securely locked. page_data: CHILD RESTRAINT SYSTEM (CRS) TATA MOTORS strongly recommends the use of Child Restraint Systems (CRS) for all children up to age of 12 years and to be placed at recommended positions only. Children travelling without recommended CRS and seated at other positions may face serious injuries in case of a collision. CRS can be installed in the vehicle using seat belts and/or ISOFIX only (if equipped) or ISOFIX with Top Tether (if equipped) or ISOFIX with support leg. If the child seat is equipped with support leg(s), always fit the support leg(s) directly to the floor. Never fit support leg(s) to a footrest or on any other object. The harness system of CRS holds the child in place, and in a collision, acts to keep the child positioned in the seat and reduce the risk of injuries. All children below age of two years must always ride in a rear-facing infant CRS. Keep children in a forward-facing CRS with a harness until they reach the size or weight limit allowed by your CRS manu facturer. Once your child outgrows the forward-fac ing CRS, your child is ready for a booster seat. Selection and Installation of CRS Always select the CRS that complies with latest safety standards (AIS072 / ECE R44). The CRS are classified according to the childs size, height and weight. Select the appropriate CRS for your child. Ensure that the CRS is securely installed in the vehicle and subsequently child fits prop erly in it and wears harness of CRS. For installation, please refer CRS manufac turers instruction manual.

tab_data:
<tab>The table provides insights into the recommended positions for installing child restraint systems (CRS) in vehicles based on the child's age and weight groups. It offers a comprehensive view of the suitability of different seating positions within the vehicle for various child age and weight categories.

For the '0' group, which encompasses children weighing up to 10kg and aged up to 9 months, the table indicates that the front passenger seat is unsuitable for them. The rear outer positions, both on the left and right sides, are marked as 'U,' signifying that they are suitable for universal category restraints. The '0+' group, catering to children up to 13kg and 24 months old, aligns with the previous group's recommendations. This implies that the front seat is still not suitable, while the rear outer positions are recommended for universal category restraints.

As we move to the 'I' group, which is for children weighing between 9 and 18kg and aged from 9 months to 48 months, the table suggests that the front seat remains unsuitable. However, the rear outer positions are now marked as 'U,L,' meaning they are suitable for both universal and specific vehicle restraints. This pattern continues for the 'II' group, catering to children aged approximately 3 to 7 years and weighing between 15 and 25kg. The front seat is mentioned as unsuitable, while the rear outer positions are recommended for universal and particular vehicle restraints.

Finally, the 'III' group, intended for older children weighing between 22 and 36kg and approximately 6 to 12 years old, maintains the unsuitability of the front seat and suggests that the rear center and outer positions are suitable for universal restraints. The table also includes a cautionary note emphasizing the potential dangers of seating a child in the front seat, highlighting the risk of serious injury or even death in the event of a collision.</tab>

tab_data:
<tab>The table describes the different states of a vehicle's immobilizer system, which is an anti-theft device designed to prevent vehicle theft. The system electronically disables the engine ignition unless the correct programmed key is used. 

When the ignition is off, a blinking immobilizer lamp indicates that the vehicle is locked and immobilized, awaiting the electronic key to unlock it. 

If the ignition is on and the immobilizer lamp is off, the vehicle is in a normal state and can be started. However, if the ignition is on and the immobilizer lamp is blinking, it signifies a potential issue. It could mean either a problem with the key, such as using a wrong key, or a problem with the immobilizer system itself. In both cases, contact with a TATA MOTORS Authorized Service Center is recommended. 

Lastly, if the ignition is on, the immobilizer lamp is on, and the vehicle is unlocked, it indicates a serious problem. Immediately contact a TATA MOTORS Authorized Service Center to resolve the issue.

The table also includes a note about the importance of using only the flip key, as the vehicle cannot be started without it. It emphasizes the need to keep a spare key safe and notes that the key tag number is essential for obtaining new or spare keys.</tab>

page_data: ANTI-LOCK BRAKING SYSTEM (ABS) ABS regulates brake pres sure in such a way that the wheels do not lock when you brake. This allows you to continue steering the vehicle when braking. page_data: ELECTRONIC BRAKE FORCE DIS TRIBUTION (EBD) EBD monitors and controls the brake pressure on the rear wheels to improve driving stability while braking. EBD provides optimal braking pressure distribution between front and rear wheels to optimize braking distance and to ensure vehicle stability by means of lowering braking pressure increase at rear wheels. BRAKE SWAY CONTROL (BSC) Detects tendency of instability during Brak ing in ABS-alone vehicles by monitoring in dividual wheel. Enhances vehicle stability by controlling braking pressure on individual wheels dur ing partial braking. STUCK MODE RECOVERY (TRAC TION PRO) (if applicable) Traction Pro mode helps the driver to get the vehicle moving if one of the front wheels is continuously spinning because of low grip from the road surface. This sit uation may arise due to road undulation, snow, mud, or any low friction surface. These situations are automatically identi fied by ABS driven Traction Pro mode and pop-up windows on the infotainment sys tem support the driver. Driver can activate the Traction pro mode and take the vehicle out of the stuck situ ation without any external assistance. Once activated, the driver will be guided of further steps via the infotainment unit itself. Traction pro mode can be used only in the forward direction and cannot be used if both front wheels are spinning. WARNING If EBD is malfunctioning, the rear wheels can lock, e.g. under full braking. page_data: KEYS A key is an electronic access and authori zation system available as a standard fea ture with your vehicle. Unlocking Principle The transponder in the ignition key carries a Unique Identification Code (UID). The vehicle unlocks when the code on the key matches with the code on the Engine Man agement Sys-tem (EMS). In case of PEPS variant, Immobilizer function is provided by PEPS ECU. Engine Starting When the key is inserted and the ignition is switched to ON, all codes are commu nicated within key, Immobilizer and EMS. The engine will start only if all the codes match. Loss Of Keys If one of the keys is lost, Contact the TATA MOTORS Authorized Dealer/Service Cen ter immediately. WARNING Do not turn ON ignition switch by using key with any type of metal wound around its grip or in contact with it. This may be detected as ab normal condition by immobilizer and prevent engine from starting. Do not turn ON ignition switch by Do not leave the key in high temper y g p ature areas. The transponder in it will behave abnormally when reused. Do not try to start the vehicle when the Immobilizer indicator lamp on the instrument cluster is glowing. tab_data:
<tab>The table details different types of keys and their respective functions. There are three types of keys: Mechanical keys, Smart Key (PEPS), and Flip Key.

Mechanical keys are described to have the ability to lock and unlock all doors. Smart Key (PEPS) has additional features like approach lights and tailgate opening, while Flip Key offers convenience with its approach light and key blade functions.

Each key type has a specific name and corresponding remote key features, contributing to different user experiences and preferences.</tab>

tab_data:
<tab>The table provides an overview of the Driver Information System, offering insights into various components and their functionalities. Notably, the odometer displays the distance traveled by the vehicle, with a unique feature of freezing the maximum value once reached, instead of resetting to zero. The trip meter, comprised of two parts labeled A and B, measures short trip distances and can be reset to begin anew after reaching 9999.9 km. 

The clock displays the current time in a 12-hour format, and its settings can be adjusted using steering wheel switches or through the infotainment system. A service reminder is also included, which provides information on the remaining days or kilometers until the next service is due. In the event of a service being overdue, a spanner symbol will flash briefly each time the ignition is turned on. 

It's important to remember that the table offers a concise glimpse of these features, and further details on vehicle-specific functionalities and the Driver Information System can be found in the accompanying manual.</tab>

tab_data:
<tab>The table contains information regarding various alert and warning messages that appear on the instrument cluster of a vehicle. Each row represents a different scenario, indicating a specific alert or warning message and its corresponding action or recommendation.

The first scenario, designated as Sn 1, signals a "Fuel Level Low State," warning the driver about the low fuel level in the vehicle. It recommends taking action by displaying the message "Fuel Level Low" on the instrument cluster.

Sn 2 is related to passenger safety. It urges the co-driver to fasten their seat belt by displaying the message "Fasten Co-Driver Seat Belt." This reminder ensures that all passengers are secured safely inside the vehicle.

Similarly, Sn 3 focuses on the driver's safety, prompting them to fasten their seat belt. The instrument cluster will show the message "Fasten Driver Seat Belt" as a reminder to secure the driver's seat belt.

In the fourth scenario, Sn 4, the vehicle's system warns the driver of exceeding the speed limit. The message "Over Speeding Detected Slow Down" appears on the instrument cluster, advising the driver to reduce their speed for a safer driving experience.

These warning messages are designed to enhance the driver's awareness, promote safety, and potentially prevent accidents or violations. The instrument cluster plays a crucial role in communicating these important alerts to the driver and passengers, ensuring a more cautious and informed driving manner.</tab>

page_data: Driver Information System (DIS) Driver Information System Image Description Indicates distance travelled by a vehicle. The Odometer reading does not re turn to 0 when maximum value is reached, the display will freeze to maximum value. Trip meter A & B The trip meter can be used to measure the distance travelled on short trips or between fuel stops. It can be reset to 0. The Trip meter reading becomes 0.0 after it crosses 9999.9 km. Indicates current time in AM/PM mode. Clock time can be changed using SET & MODE knob. Whenever the battery terminals or related fuses are connected, you must reset the clock time. This feature is available when ignition switch is in ON position. NOTE: Clock settings can also be changed through infotainment system. For more information, refer infotainment manual. Door Ajar This warning will be indicated when the drivers door or front passenger door is open. This indicates how many days/kilometres are left till service is due. If service is overdue, it will display 0 km or 0 days and a spanner symbol will blink every time ignition is ON for a few seconds. Never reset the display between service intervals as it may give incorrect readings. The information is retained in the service interval display even after the vehicle battery is disconnected. NOTE: This option is for indicative purpose only. Keep track of your odometer reading and follow the maintenance schedule. Odometer Clock Service reminder
tab_data:
<tab>The table contains information about various features of a vehicle's Driver Information System. The first column presents the names of the features, the second column has a corresponding image or name of the feature, and the last column describes the function of each feature. 

The Odometer feature shows the distance traveled by the vehicle and does not reset to zero but instead freezes when the maximum value is reached. The Trip Meter A & B can measure short trip distances or those between fuel stops and can be reset to zero. It resets to 0.0 after reaching 9999.9 km.

The Clock feature displays the current time in AM/PM format and allows for time adjustments using the 'SET' and 'MODE' knobs. The Door Ajar warning notifies the driver when the driver's door or front passenger door is open.
 
Additionally, the Service Reminder informs the driver about the remaining days or kilometers until the next service is due. It's important not to reset the display between service intervals to avoid incorrect readings. The system retains this information even after disconnecting the vehicle battery.

This table provides a summary of the key features of the Driver Information System, offering clarity to users who require a straightforward understanding of these in-car technologies.</tab>

<tab>The table provides information on the warning lamps and their functionalities in a vehicle, likely a car. Each row details a specific lamp's attributes, starting with the name of the warning lamp and its corresponding color. The "Indicator" column describes the function of the lamp, and the "Remarks" column provides additional notes and instructions.

The Malfunction Indication Lamp (MIL) is amber in color and illuminates to indicate an engine-related fault that may increase the vehicle's emission levels beyond regulatory standards. Contacting a Tata Motors authorized dealer is recommended for rectification. Similarly, the Check Engine Lamp, also amber, alerts the driver to faults in the Engine Management System and requires a visit to the authorized dealer for diagnosis.

The Immobilizer lamp, if available, is red. It disables the engine from starting unless the original key is used. Its blinking indicates a vehicle immobilized condition, while a constant glow could mean a problem with the key or the system. Contacting the Tata Motors service center is advised in such cases.

Lastly, the Turn Signal lamp is green and indicates the direction of the turn, blinking when the indicator is operated. It also flashes simultaneously with the hazard switch, regardless of the ignition status, and is accompanied by a tick-tock sound.

In summary, the table details the meanings and indications of various warning lamps in a vehicle, emphasizing the importance of specific colors and providing insights into the corresponding actions to take in case of illumination.</tab>

tab_data:
<tab>The table provides information on the various warning lamps that can appear in a vehicle and their meanings. Each row in the table represents a different warning lamp and provides details on its function.

The first row indicates that the blue high beam lamp lights up when the high beam headlamps are switched on or flashed. 

The low oil pressure indicator, represented by a red lamp, will remain on if there's a fault in the electrical circuit or lubrication system. The driver is advised to contact a Tata Motors service center to rectify the issue.

Another red lamp lights up when the ignition is switched on, indicating battery charging. If it stays lit while the engine runs, it signifies a possible issue with battery charging. The suggestion is to try increasing the engine rpm to 3000 for 15 minutes and see if the lamp turns off after a cycle of ignition on and off.

The airbag status lamp, also red, lights up when the ignition is switched on and goes off afterward. If it continuously blinks, it requires immediate attention, and the driver should contact the Tata Motors Authorized Dealer/Service Center.

The final row describes a red lamp that comes on briefly when the ignition is turned on. If it stays lit after the parking brake is released, it signals either a low brake fluid level or an Electronic Braking Distribution (EBD) malfunction. 

The table provides a clear description of these warning lamps and their corresponding actions or indications. Understanding these warnings is crucial, as they provide important information about the vehicle's status and any potential issues that need attention.</tab>

<tab>The table provides information on various warning lamps and their functionalities. When the ignition is switched on, some lamps illuminate to provide indications and warnings about different vehicle systems. The cruise control lamp, often green in color, turns off once the engine is started and indicates the activation of the cruise control feature. If the engine overheats, the high coolant temperature lamp, usually red, will blink and emit an audible warning. It's important not to remove the radiator pressure cap when the engine is hot and to seek assistance from a TATA MOTORS service center. 

The ABS warning lamp, often amber, lights up briefly when the ignition is switched on. If the lamp remains on, it signals a potential malfunction in the ABS. Normal braking systems continue to operate without ABS assistance. Drivers are advised to contact a TATA MOTORS dealer or service center for further diagnosis. There's also a lamp associated with the sport mode, which illuminates in an amber color when activated, indicating the availability of increased torque.

Overall, the table offers a clear description of the purposes of these warning lamps and their corresponding actions or indications. Understanding these indicators is essential for drivers, as they provide valuable insights into the vehicle's status and potential issues that may require immediate attention.</tab>

The "Daytime Running Lamps (DRL)" are green in color and have a dual function: they turn on with the ignition and switch off after the engine starts, and they also illuminate when the Daytime Running lamp is on. A notable point is that the parking lamps should be on to initiate the DRLs. 

Another mentioned lamp is the "Door Ajar" lamp, which is a bi-colored White and Red. This lamp provides an individual indication for all four doors and the tailgate, signaling their open status. The front passenger seat belt indicator is designed to ensure safety. It remains lit in red until the co-driver's seatbelt is buckled. If the vehicle reaches a speed of 15 kmph and the seatbelt isn't fastened, an audio warning is issued for 90 seconds. Fastening the seatbelt disengages the buzzer and turns off the warning lamp. Additionally, the seatbelt reminder shuts off when the reverse gear is engaged. 

There's also a speed limit warning indicator, which lights up in amber. It's designed to alert the driver when the vehicle surpasses 80 kmph, emitting an audible chime every two minutes as a continuous reminder. Overall, the table offers a comprehensive overview of the warning lamp system, serving as a helpful reference for understanding the various indicators and their purposes.</tab>

page_data: Warning Lamps Color Indicator Remarks If vehicle speed crosses 120 kmph, the speed limit warning indicator flashes along with an audio warning continuously, until the vehicle speed is above 120 kmph. If vehicle speed is between 80 kmph and 120 kmph, then the audio warning will become less frequent but the speed limit warning Indicator will remain ON continuously. When the vehicle speed is reduced below 80 kmph, then the speed limit warning indicator and the audio warning will turn off. ECO (if available) Green CITY White / Blue DPF (if available) Amber The lamp comes on when ignition is switched ON. Once engine is started, it turns OFF. When ECO lamp is ON, it indicates the car is in Economy drive mode, which helps to achieve a better fuel economy. The lamp comes on when ignition is switched ON. Once engine is started, it turns OFF. If CITY lamp is ON, it indicates City drive mode, which helps to achieve op timum torque and fuel economy. The DPF warning light or symbol switches ON continuously to indicate that the DPF needs to eliminate the trapped pollutants (particulate matter) through the re-generation procedure. The warning light or symbol switch ON only when driving conditions require the driver to be notified. DPF ON does not indicate a malfunction. To switch off the warning light or symbol, keep the car running on road until regeneration is complete (ideally at 3rd gear, 50-80 kmph, with engine speed over 2000 rpm). The process normally takes about 20 minutes.
tab_data:
<tab>The table contains information about the warning lamps and their corresponding features. The first row serves as headers for each column: 'Warning Lamps', 'Color', 'Indicator', 'Remarks'. The subsequent rows describe the function of each warning lamp and their respective colors and indications.

The speed limit warning indicator, which is triggered when the vehicle speed exceeds 120 km/h, flashes along with an audio warning. The indicator remains on continuously until the speed goes above 120 km/h. A less frequent audio warning is sounded if the vehicle speed is between 80 and 120 km/h, but the indicator stays on. When the speed drops below 80 km/h, both the audio warning and the indicator are turned off.

The ECO lamp, marked by a green color, illuminates when the ignition is switched on, and turns off once the engine is started. This indicates that the car is in 'Economy' mode, which is fuel-efficient. Similarly, the CITY lamp, with a white or blue color, illuminates when the ignition is switched on and turns off after the engine start. A lit CITY lamp signifies that the vehicle is in 'City' drive mode, which focuses on providing optimal torque and fuel economy.

The DPF lamp, represented by an amber color, signals the need for the diesel particulate filter to regenerate. This occurs when the trapped pollutants require elimination. The warning remains continuously until the regeneration procedure is complete, which ideally happens within 20 minutes, under specific driving conditions.

The table provides a clear summary of the warning lamps, their colors, and the corresponding indications and remarks for a better understanding of their functionalities.</tab>

This warning light does not indicate a malfunction but rather a necessary cleaning process.

<tab>The table contains information regarding various warning lamps and their corresponding indicators and remarks. The first row establishes that the warning light remains off during the Diesel Particulate Filter (DPF) regeneration procedure and explains the consequences of not following this procedure. This lamp indicates a fault in the Automatic Manual Transmission system, and immediate attention from a TATA MOTORS authorized service center is recommended.</tab>

page_data: STARTING THE ENGINE Make sure that parking brake is engaged and vehicle is in neutral gear. Press the clutch pedal fully and crank the engine. Do not press the accelerator pedal when starting the engine. Release the key as soon as the engine starts. Repeat if engine does not start. Driving (AMT) Climbing Sharp Gradients Apply the parking brake firmly so that the vehicle does not roll backwards. Shift the gearshift lever to the A position while depressing the brake pedal. Make sure that the gear position indicator in the instrument cluster displays 1st gear. Release the brake pedal and depress the accelerator pedal gradually, and when the vehicle starts to move, release the parking brake and depress the accelerator pedal to start off. On climbing sharp gradients, never hold the vehicle at a stop using only the accel erator pedal or the creeping function. If you perform this operation for a certain pe riod of time, this can also cause excessive damage to the clutch. Descending Sharp Gradients Depress the brake pedal and shift the gear shift lever to the A position. Make sure that the gear position indicator in the in strumental cluster displays 1st gear. Release the brake pedal and depress the accelerator pedal slowly. Even if the accel erator pedal is not depressed, the clutch will be engaged when the vehicle speed increases. This could cause the brakes to over heat, resulting in reduced braking effi ciency. Failure to take this precaution could result in loss of vehicle control. WARNING WARNING The engine emits poisonous exhaust gases such as carbon monoxide. Inhal ing these exhaust gases leads to poi soning. There is a risk of serious health problems. Therefore, never leave the engine running in enclosed spaces without sufficient ventilation. When descending on sharp gradients, NEVER turn the ignition key to the OFF position. Emission control system damage may result. NOTE After starting, run the engine in idle speed for at least 30 seconds. Do not press accelerator pedal while starting the engine to avoid damage to tur bocharger. WARNING Try not to hold the brake pedal down too long or too often while going down a steep or long hill.

tab_data: <tab>The table details how the Drive Mode affects vehicle performance. There are two primary drive modes - CITY and ECO. The CITY drive mode optimizes the car for balanced performance, increasing engine torque and power output. It is the default mode and engages at every ignition cycle. On the other hand, the ECO mode prioritizes fuel efficiency, offering optimum engine torque and power for a more economical driving experience. These modes can be selected using a switch on the center console. The Instrument Cluster's Driver Information display (DIS) indicates the engaged gear position. The drive mode selection adapts the engine characteristics and overall vehicle performance to the driver's needs.</tab>

Some more 10-amp fuses are F13 and F14, which power the EMS battery and compressor. Finally, F15, rated at 25 amps, is assigned to the ABS ECU battery. 

It's important to note that the fuse box layout is provided for reference only, and there's a note emphasizing that one should refer to the sticker inside the fuse box cover for more accurate information.</tab>

The first fuse, F16, is designated for the horn battery and has a rating of 15A. Nearby, F17 is responsible for the brake lamp battery, rated at 10A. Moving along, we find fuses related to various vital functions such as the ABS pump (F18) rated at 40A, the interior front battery (F19) rated at 60A, and the ignition load (F20), also rated at 60A. 

F21 is assigned to the ignition coil, rated at 15A, while the following two fuses, F22 and F23, are marked as dashes, indicating perhaps that they are unused or not currently in use. The final group of fuses is related to the EMS system and wiper motor. tab_data: <tab>The table outlines response times for a 24/7 road assistance program offered by Tata Motors in partnership with TVS AA. The assistance is categorized into three scenarios. For breakdowns occurring within city limits, the response time is promised to be within 60 minutes. If the breakdown happens on state or national highways, the response time extends to 90 minutes. Finally, for ghats and other places, the estimated response time is 120 minutes, with a disclaimer that the timing may vary based on factors like location, terrain, traffic, and time of day. The varying response times aim to ensure that someone experiencing vehicle trouble is promptly attended to, depending on their location.</tab>

tab_data:
<tab>The table provides insights into maintaining the functionality of a vehicle, specifically focusing on tire pressure, its relation to inflation, and the resulting tire wear. It offers a clear guideline for understanding the consequences of incorrect tire pressure. 

Starting with the importance of maintaining correct tire pressure, the information emphasizes that under-inflation leads to excessive side tread wear. This issue can be detrimental, as it not only affects the vehicle's performance but also accelerates the tire's deterioration. The table suggests that the recommended pressure range for optimal performance and safety is 0.8 to 0.9 mm. 

In contrast, over-inflation causes excessive central tread wear. While this might not seem as harmful as under-inflation, it nevertheless results in an uneven and inefficient wear pattern, which could eventually compromise the vehicle's handling and stability. 

Correct tire pressure, on the other hand, promotes uniform wear, ensuring the tires' longevity and preserving the vehicle's overall performance. The text also emphasizes the importance of periodic checks, not only for pressure but also for the general condition of the tires, which, if ignored, could lead to unforeseen complications. 

Furthermore, the safety precautions related to tire maintenance are emphasized, especially concerning the battery. The battery, containing sulphuric acid, poses a potential hazard, warranting caution during maintenance and urging the use of protective gear. 

Lastly, the summary stresses the significance of using recommended spark plugs for replacement purposes, ensuring vehicle compatibility and performance. Overall, the data serves as a concise manual for tire maintenance, highlighting the interplay of pressure, inflation, and wear, while also addressing safety concerns and the use of appropriate replacements parts.</tab>

page_data: ON BOARD DIAGNOSTIC (OBD II) SYSTEM On board Diagnostics or OBD, is an auto motive term referring to a vehicles self-di agnostic and reporting capability. The OBD system allows continuous diagnosis of the components of the vehicle corre lated with emissions. This system warns the driver, by turning ON the Malfunction Indication lamp (MIL) on the instrument cluster, when a fault causes emission lev els to increase. The OBD system also has a diagnostic connector that can be interfaced with ap propriate diagnostic tools, which makes it possible to read the fault codes stored in the Electronic Control Unit, together with a series of specific parameters for Engine operation and Diagnosis. This check can also be carried out by the traffic police. Location of On board diagnostic (OBD II) On board diagnostic located in Engine compartment fuse box. (Refer below image) NOTE Use CR 2032 battery only. An inappropriately dis-posed battery can be harmful to the environment and human health. Dispose the bat tery according to your local law(s) and regulation.

page_data: CAR CARE Your vehicle is subjected to many external influences such as climate, road condi tions, industrial pollution and proximity to the sea. These conditions demand regular care of the vehicle body. Dirt, insects, bird droppings, oil, grease, fuel and stone chip pings should be removed as soon as pos sible. Washing Following these tips while washing your vehicle. Always wash your vehicle in shade and the surface is at room temperature. Wash with mild vehicle wash soap like Car Shampoo and use a soft bristle brush, sponge or soft cloth and rinse it fre quently while washing to avoid scratches. To avoid scratches, please wear soft gloves. Remove finger rings, nails, wrist watch while washing. To remove stubborn stains and contami nants like tar, use turpentine or cleaners like Stain remover which are safe for paint surfaces. Avoid substances like petrol, diesel, kerosene, benzene, thinner, ac-ids or other solvents that cause damage to paint. Dry your vehicle thoroughly to pre-vent any damp spots. Rinse all surfaces thoroughly to prevent any traces of soap and other cleaners as this may lead to the formation of stains on the painted surface later. After drying the vehicle, inspect it for chips and scratches that could allow corrosion to start. Apply touch up paint where nec essary. Cleaning of Carpets Vacuum clean the carpet regularly to re move dirt. Dirt will make the carpet wear out faster. Periodically, shampoo the car pet to keep it looking new. Use carpet cleaners (preferably foam type). Follow the instructions that come with the cleaner. Apply it with a sponge or soft brush. Keep the carpeting as dry as possible by not adding water to the foam. WARNING Do not direct high pressure washer fluid/ water jets (Pres-sure above 0.5 bar) at electrical devices and connecter during washing. This is to prevent mal- function / failure of electrical sys-tem due to water ingress. NOTE Avoid parking the car under trees with out proper cover, it will reduce the amount of bird droppings, tree sap and pollen contact on paint surface. Regu larly remove the twigs, leaves and veg etation near the windshield areas, to avoid water stagnation.

ENVIRONMENTAL SAFETY TATA MOTORS PASSENGER VEHICLE LIMITED is committed to pro-duce vehicles using environmentally sus- tainable technology. A number of features have been incorporated in TATA MOTORS passenger vehicles which have been de- signed to ensure environmental compati- bility throughout the life cycle of the vehicle. We would like to inform you that your vehicle meets BS VI emission norms and this is being regularly validated at the manufacturing stages. Monitor the vehicles fuel consumption regularly and if showing rising trend get the vehicle immediately attended at the Companys Authorised Service Outlets. get it attended immediately. Use only recommended grades and specified quantity of lubricants. Get your vehicle checked for emission periodically by an authorised dealer. Switch off the engine during long stops at traffic jams or signals. If you need to keep the engine running, avoid unnec- essary revving it or stopping and start- ing. Check Air filter, fuel filter and oil filter periodically and replaced, if required, as recommended by TATA MOTORS. It is not necessary to rev the engine before turning it off as it unnecessarily burns fuel. Do not pour used oils or coolants into the sewage drains, garden soil or open streams. Dispose the used filters and batteries in compliance with the current legislation. As a user you too can protect the environ-ment by operating your vehicle in a proac-tive manner. A lot depends on your driving style and the way you maintain your vehi-cle. We have given a few tips for your guidance. Driving Shift to higher gears as soon as it is possible. Use each gear upto 2/3rd of its maximum engine speed. Do not allow unauthorized person to tamper with engine settings or to carry modifications on the vehicle. A chart indicating gear shifting speeds is given in this book. Maintenance Never allow the vehicle to run out of fuel. Parts like brake liners, clutch discs should be vacuum cleaned. Do not use compressed air for cleaning these parts, which may spread hazardous dust in the atmosphere. g Avoid frequent and violent accelera- Ensure that recommended mainte- nance is carried out on the vehicle reg- ularly at the Authorised Service Outlets. tion. Do not carry any unnecessary weight in the vehicle as it overloads the en- gine.
